column2: Agilent-011521 Human 1A Microarray G4110A  (Feature Number version)
column4: Agilent's Human 1A Oligo Microarray (V2) includes over 17K 60-mer oligonucleotide probes, sourced from the Incyte Foundation Database and are designed to span conserved exons across the transcripts of the targeted full length genes. Coupled with Agilent's probe selection and validation processes, this design method gives the customer maximum confidence in data quality and prevents redundancy in gene coverage. Arrays of this design have barcodes that begin with 16011521 or 2511521. Orientation: Features are numbered numbered Left-to-Right, Top-to-Bottom as scanned by an Agilent scanner (barcode on the left, DNA on the back surface, scanned through the glass), matching the FeatureNum output from Agilent's Feature Extraction software. The ID column represents the Agilent Feature Extraction feature number. Rows and columns are numbered as scanned by an Axon Scanner (barcode on the bottom, DNA on the front surface). To match data scanned on an Axon scanner, use the RefNumber column contained in the Agilent-provided GAL file as the ID_REF column in sample submissions. *** A different version of this platform with the Agilent Probe names in the ID column is assigned accession number GPL7260.

column2: SuperArray GEArray Q Series Human Extracellular Matrix and Adhesion Molecules Gene Array
column4: SuperArray GEArray Q Series Human Extracellular Matrix and Adhesion Molecules Gene Array contains 96 genes encoding proteins important for the attachment of cells to their surroundings. The array includes various types of cell adhesion molecules (such as the intregrins, IgG superfamily members, cadherins and catenins, and selectins) as well as extracellular matrix proteins, proteases (such as the matrix metalloproteinases and the serine and cysteine proteinases) and their inhibitors. These proteins play key roles in mediating cell-cell, cell-tissue and cell-extracellular matrix interactions and are involved in the normal processes of cell growth, division, differentiation, migration, as well as apoptosis. These genes are also important in many diseases and pathophysiological processes, including tumor invasion and metastasis, rheumatoid arthritis, cardiovascular disorders, wound healing, inflammation, and some central nervous diseases. Through a simple side-by-side hybridization using your experimental RNA samples and the arrays and reagents provided in the kit, you can simultaneously determine the expression profile of these matrix and adhesion molecules in your model system.

The goal of the Mammalian Gene Collection (MGC), a trans-NIH initiative, is to provide full-length open reading frame (FL-ORF) clones for human, mouse, and rat genes. In 2005, the project added the cow cDNAs generated by Genome Canada. Initially, cDNA libraries provided the source of the clones. Recently, alternative methods based on gene-specific amplification have been developed to target the recovery of human and mouse genes absent from the MGC collection.

column2: University of Goettingen TAL UniGene_Set_RZPD2_mm2 pattern 06102003
column4: Preparation of high-density cDNA microarrays. PCR-based cDNA amplification (Hedge et al., 2000 PMID: 10997270) was used to generate DNA from a murine cDNA clone library (Mouse Unigene Set RZPD 2) purchased from the RZPD (http://www.rzpd.de). This murine library contained 21,826 non-redundant clones from diverse tissues. After fully automated PCR-amplification and ultrafiltration-based purification using a Beckman-Coulter cDNA-production unit, control gel electrophoresis was perfomed showing that 95% of the products were clonally amplified. Non clonal or failed PCR-products were excluded from data analysis. The PCR-products were spotted on epoxy-coated glass slides (Schott Nexterion) using the BioRad spotter "Virtek Chip-Writer Pro" with 48 split pins (purchased from Telechem, www.arrayit.com). The arrays were prepared for hybridisation using surface blocking as described by the slide manufacturer. Keywords = cDNA, microarray, spotted, PCR-products

The Sentrix Human-6 BeadChip can be used to study expression of over 47,000 human transcripts. Researchers can generate whole-genome expression profiles for 6 samples in parallel on a single BeadChip. Array is composed of 3 micron features with average feature redundancy of 30-fold . All features are QCed by sequential hybridizations process called array decoding. Probes are fully screened all-full-length 50-mers. Assay requires 50-100ng of total RNA input. Array content is based on RefSeq and additional space is occupied by targets selected from Unigene build 163 and Gnomon databases.

The Sentrix HumanRef-8 BeadChip can be used to study expression of over 23,000 human transcripts from the NCBI RefSeq database. Researchers can generate whole-genome expression profiles for 8 samples in parallel on a single BeadChip. The array is composed of 3 micron features with average feature redundancy of 30-fold. All features are quality controlled by sequential hybridizations process called array decoding. Probes are fully screened, full-length 50-mers. Assay requires 50-100ng of total RNA input.

HumanMethylation27 DNA Analysis BeadChip allows researchers to interrogate 27,578 highly informative CpG sites per sample at single-nucleotide resolution. This 12-sample BeadChip features content derived from the well-annotated NCBI CCDS database (Genome Build 36) and is supplemented with more than 1,000 cancer-related genes described in published literature. Probe content has been enriched to deeply cover more than 150 well-established cancer genes known to show differential methylation patterns. HumanMethylation27 BeadChip content also targets the promoter regions of 110 miRNA genes.
